{
  "doc_id": "16879",
  "text": "DHFR from E. coli has been extensively characterized by a range of biophysical techniques. Both crystallographic and NMR studies show that the M20 loop region of this enzyme adopts several conformations relative to the active site as the catalytic cycle progresses, and suggests that the movement of this loop might modulate the turnover rate by limiting the rate of product dissociation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In another study, fluorescence microscopy and ensemble kinetics were used to study conformational transitions associated with enzyme catalysis [CITATION_5] . Recently, Hecht, Benkovic and co-workers introduced two pyrenylalanine chromophores into DHFR, which led to excimer formation at the reactive state [CITATION_6] . This experiment provided a more direct demonstration that kcat is governed by a conformational change after the hydride transfer step. Another NMR study of DHFR in complex with a variety of ligands also suggested that changes in the dynamics of the enzyme may be correlated with kinetic events along the catalytic cycle [CITATION_7] .",
